  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4104345049" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4104345049" />
    <a title="Nick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/49166304-nick"><img alt="Nick" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4104345049?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nick" href="/user/show/49166304-nick">Nick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/49166304-nick?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/49166304-nick?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/49166304-nick?shelf=mafia">mafia</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4104345049" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8843863378279488295">I really like the movie and rewatched it as I was reading the book. If one is to believe the trivia section om IMDb, Pistone claimed that the movie was 85 percent accurate. Having read the book I would say that the ratio is the opposite. I fully understand that one may have to combine characters, compress timelines etc. to make the story flow in a different medium. For a masterclass in adaptation check out <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/158141.Wiseguy' title='Wiseguy by Nicholas Pileggi' rel='nofollow noopener'>Wiseguy</a> and <a href='https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0099685/' rel='nofollow noopener'>Goodfellas</a>. But Donnie Brasco the movie is very, very different from the book </span>
  <span id="freeText8843863378279488295" style="display:none">I really like the movie and rewatched it as I was reading the book. If one is to believe the trivia section om IMDb, Pistone claimed that the movie was 85 percent accurate. Having read the book I would say that the ratio is the opposite. I fully understand that one may have to combine characters, compress timelines etc. to make the story flow in a different medium. For a masterclass in adaptation check out <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/158141.Wiseguy" title="Wiseguy by Nicholas Pileggi" rel="nofollow noopener">Wiseguy</a> and <a href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0099685/" rel="nofollow noopener">Goodfellas</a>. But Donnie Brasco the movie is very, very different from the book and the movie clearly comes out on top. It's not a bad book, but it could have been so much better.<br /><br />Pistone was not a writer when this book was released. Which is fine, but one would expect the ghostwriter to assume a larger responsibility in this situation. But having read the book it's unclear what role Richard Woodley played other than perhaps checking punctuation at best. Because the book is so poorly written at times that it becomes a distraction. It's writing at high school level. I don't expect a book like this to be written in florid iambic pentameter, but a vocabulary as rudimentary as the one in this book came as a surprise. How many times can you fit the word <i>guy</i> in a small paragraph?<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>Albert was a half-ass wiseguy—just a connected guy, not a made guy. He was a big guy, maybe 6’ 2”, about thirty years old. He was a con artist dealing in paper—a stocks-and-bonds type guy.<br /><br />(Chapter 4)</i>
</blockquote><br /><br />The book is full of repetition. Like the following section where these two adjacent paragraphs say the exact same thing, but in slightly different words as if trying to up the word count in a high school paper:<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>There wasn’t one hour of one day that went by when they weren’t thinking and talking about what they were going to steal, who or what or where they were going to rob. There was always a load to go after, or somebody else’s load you might get a piece of, always something to hustle.<br /><br />When they got up in the morning, they didn’t think about going to work and punching a time clock. They didn’t think about spending time with their wives or girlfriends. The mob was their job. You got up, went to the club or wherever you hung out, and spent your day with those guys.<br /><br />(Chapter 5)</i>
</blockquote><br /><br />Another linguistic peculiarity is the switch between past and present tense in the descriptive text (not the direct quotes), which doesn't make much sense:<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>Sonny <u>called</u> at ten o‘clock. I <u>met</u> him in the lounge at the restaurant. We <u>had</u> a drink before we left. I didn’t say anything about having seen Trafficante.<br /><br />“He’s a dynamite guy,” Sonny <u>says</u>. “He likes me. We got whatever we want. All the doors are open to us in Florida now, just so we do things properly. A fifty-fifty split. If we fuck up, Donnie, the old man will shut every door on us. One of the things we should start looking at, he said, was bingo. He’s big in bingo, but he doesn’t have any in Pasco County. Big money in that.”<br /><br />In the car, Sonny <u>unwound</u>. “It was a feeling-out conversation,” he <u>says</u>. “I told him, ‘Listen, I’m no sophisticated person. I’m a street person all my life.’ I says, ‘I love the streets, you know. I don’t know nothing about nothing, about gambling or anything.’ I says, ‘Me, I just like to go in the street, rob who the fuck I gotta rob.’ ”<br /><br />(Chapter 14)</i>
</blockquote><br /><br />The later parts of the book, especially chapter 17, is almost all dialogue without much commentary, I assume verbatim from surveillance tapes. At times it's near incomprehensible and after a while almost feels like padding. this was a slog to read. The book does a poor job explaining the developments in the Bonanno family. I would recommend reading something like <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/652063.Five_Families_The_Rise__Decline__and_Resurgence_of_America_s_Most_Powerful_Mafia_Empires" title="Five Families The Rise, Decline, and Resurgence of America's Most Powerful Mafia Empires by Selwyn Raab" rel="nofollow noopener">Five Families: The Rise, Decline, and Resurgence of America's Most Powerful Mafia Empires</a> before reading Donnie Brasco.<br /><br />By the way, the nicknames are amazing. Frankie Fish, Porkie, Bobby Smash, Johnny Spaghetti, Jimmy Legs. I might consider a career in the mafia if it means I get an awesome nickname like that.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8843863378279488295" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


